---
import { Image } from 'astro:assets';
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { SITE_DATA } from '../constants';
import portraitImage from '../assets/portrait.svg';

import '../styles/about.css';

// ============================================================================
// CUSTOMIZATION GUIDE
// ============================================================================
// This is the About page of your academic website. To customize:
// 1. Update the intro paragraph with your background and interests
// 2. Replace work experience items with your positions
// 3. Update education section with your degrees
// 4. The portrait image is loaded from src/assets/portrait.svg (replace with your own)
// 5. Contact information automatically uses data from src/constants.ts
---

<Layout pageTitle="About">
    <div class="page-container">
        <h1>About me</h1>

        <div class="about-content">
            <div class="about-intro-wrapper centered-column">
                <div class="about-header centered-column">
                    <Image src={portraitImage} alt={SITE_DATA.name} class="about-portrait" />
                    <h2 class="about-name">{SITE_DATA.name}</h2>
                </div>

                <p class="intro-text">
                    I am a <strong>physical chemist</strong> and <strong>X-ray crystallographer</strong> whose research
                    fundamentally shaped our understanding of molecular structures. My work produced the critical X-ray
                    diffraction images that revealed the helical structure of DNA, most notably <strong>Photo 51</strong>,
                    which provided the key evidence for the double helix model. Beyond DNA, I made pioneering contributions
                    to understanding the molecular structures of viruses and coal. My commitment to rigorous experimental
                    methodology and precise interpretation of data exemplifies the highest standards of scientific inquiry.
                </p>
            </div>

            <section>
                <h2>Research & Positions</h2>
                <ul class="work-list icon-list">
                    <li>
                        <div class="list-entry">
                            <h3>Research Scientist</h3>
                            <p class="institution">Birkbeck College, University of London, 1953-1958</p>
                            <p>Led groundbreaking research on the molecular structure of viruses, particularly the tobacco mosaic
                            virus and polio virus. My work established fundamental principles of virus structure and assembly,
                            demonstrating that viruses could be studied as crystalline materials. This research opened new avenues
                            for understanding viral diseases.</p>
                        </div>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <div class="list-entry">
                            <h3>Research Associate</h3>
                            <p class="institution">King's College London, 1951-1953</p>
                            <p>Conducted pioneering X-ray diffraction studies of DNA fibers that produced the famous "Photo 51,"
                            the clearest image of DNA structure obtained to date. My meticulous experimental work and mathematical
                            analysis demonstrated the helical nature of DNA and provided crucial measurements of its dimensions.
                            This work was foundational to understanding the molecular basis of heredity, though my contributions
                            were not properly acknowledged during my lifetime.</p>
                        </div>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <div class="list-entry">
                            <h3>Research Officer</h3>
                            <p class="institution">British Coal Utilisation Research Association, 1942-1947</p>
                            <p>Investigated the physical structure of coals and carbonized coals, work that earned my doctorate.
                            My research clarified the relationship between coal structure and its properties, contributing to
                            improved industrial applications. This early work established my expertise in X-ray crystallography
                            and materials science.</p>
                        </div>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <div class="list-entry">
                            <h3>Postdoctoral Researcher</h3>
                            <p class="institution">Laboratoire Central des Services Chimiques de l'État, Paris, 1947-1950</p>
                            <p>Advanced my X-ray diffraction techniques and applied them to the study of carbon structures.
                            Mastered the use of X-ray crystallography for analyzing complex molecular arrangements, skills
                            that would prove essential for my later DNA work.</p>
                        </div>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h2>Education</h2>
                <ul class="education-list icon-list">
                    <li>
                        <div class="education-entry">
                            <h3>PhD in Physical Chemistry</h3>
                            <p class="institution">University of Cambridge, 1945</p>
                            <p class="grade">Thesis: "The Physical Chemistry of Solid Organic Colloids with Special Reference to Coal"</p>
                        </div>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <div class="education-entry">
                            <h3>BA in Natural Sciences (Chemistry)</h3>
                            <p class="institution">Newnham College, Cambridge University, 1941</p>
                            <p class="grade">Second Class Honours - women were not granted full degrees at this time</p>
                        </div>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <div class="education-entry">
                            <h3>Secondary Education</h3>
                            <p class="institution">St Paul's Girls' School, London, 1930s</p>
                            <p class="grade">Excelled in science and mathematics from an early age</p>
                        </div>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h2>CV</h2>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <p>
                        For more information about my work and contributions:
                    </p>
                    <a href={`https://linkedin.com/in/${SITE_DATA.linkedin}`}
                       class="info-card-link"
                       target="_blank"
                       rel="noopener noreferrer"
                       aria-label="Visit my LinkedIn profile">
                        <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="60" height="60" fill="currentColor">
                            <path d="M20.5 2h-17A1.5 1.5 0 002 3.5v17A1.5 1.5 0 003.5 22h17a1.5 1.5 0 001.5-1.5v-17A1.5 1.5 0 0020.5 2zM8 19H5v-9h3zM6.5 8.25a1.75 1.75 0 110-3.5 1.75 1.75 0 010 3.5zM19 19h-3v-4.74c0-1.42-.6-1.93-1.38-1.93A1.74 1.74 0 0013 14.19V19h-3v-9h2.9v1.3a3.11 3.11 0 012.7-1.4c1.55 0 3.4 1.08 3.4 3.93z"></path>
                        </svg>
                        <span>LinkedIn</span>
                    </a>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h2>Contact</h2>
                <p>
                    If you'd like to reach out, send me an <a href={`mailto:${SITE_DATA.email}`}>e-mail</a> or connect via <a href={`https://linkedin.com/in/${SITE_DATA.linkedin}`} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">social media</a>.
                </p>
            </section>
        </div>
    </div>
</Layout>
